Theresa May's stage
London — — facing the new British Prime Minister Theresa May is a daunting task: to implement the demands of British voters — — or more accurately, voters in England and Wales — — to "exit the EU" and manage the far-reaching consequences that come with it.
The challenge she faces makes her predecessors in recent years seem inferior.
But she may have the ability to complete this task.
No one should underestimate May.
Like German Chancellor Merkel, who has proven courage in a series of crises, all the tools needed to complete the task are in May's hands.
She is smart and resilient, with no patience for nonsense.
She has a strong sense of public service and equally strong values.
She is not constrained by any ideology, is very skilled at gaining control, and operates within her self-defined boundaries to ensure she is familiar with the issues at hand.
May has won most of the battles she has been involved in, and shows no mercy to those who have used underhanded means against her.
But she has few enemies within the party and is quite popular among ordinary party members.
This is a powerful combination — — she needs to make full use of it to lead the UK's Brexit process.
The Brexit process in the UK has already begun, and this is undeniable.
Even though Scotland and Northern Ireland voted to remain in the EU, May has repeatedly stated that the Brexit referendum cannot be reversed.
She has repeatedly stated "Brexit is Brexit," and her ministers have all agreed with her view.
But May has not given a precise definition of Brexit yet.
This task is very difficult to complete.
Imagine someone telling you, "Breakfast is breakfast," and then starts preparing your food.
You would find it hard to know exactly what you will be eating.
A Northern Irish "Ulster fry" — eggs, bacon, sausage, black pudding, potatoes, soda bread, and fried tomatoes — paired with a cup of tea?
Coffee and pastries?
Depending on your environment and personal preferences, you might feel very differently about various possible combinations.
The same applies to Brexit.
Some people might be primarily concerned about preventing EU labor from entering the UK.
Others might be more concerned about gaining access to the single market.
But unlike breakfast, the UK cannot order one of every item on the menu.
The reality often overlooked by Brexit supporters is that the EU will not give the UK all the benefits for free.
This is not because EU leaders want to win popularity or punish the UK for rejecting the EU (although sometimes such inflammatory rhetoric is heard, such as the new UK Foreign Secretary Boris Johnson's "Hitler-esque imperialism").
Rather, we Britons often forget that everyone – including the EU and all its member states – has their own sworn political or commercial interests to protect.
For May, the core challenge in the coming months will be to determine, on a realistic basis, what the UK's objectives should be after the difficult negotiations on its relationship with the EU (and, in the trade area, with the world) begin.
Given the scope of the agenda (I can think of at least six major topics that need to be negotiated separately), the negotiation process may take years to complete.
(The negotiations may be completed by the time my 11-year-old granddaughter starts university!
) We must clearly prioritize to prevent the negotiation time from being even longer.
The goal, of course, is to strike a balance between British exports of goods and services (especially financial services) entering other European countries and restricting EU citizens from entering the UK.
The more concessions made in one area, the greater the concessions needed in others.
May needs to fully utilize the knowledge, skills, and political capital she possesses to ensure the reasonableness of the negotiation transactions.
Even if she succeeds in achieving her goals, she will still find discontent among all parts — it is unavoidable — not just a part of it.
This will exacerbate another major challenge faced by the May government: narrowing the growing gap in British society that has been exposed by Brexit.
The blue-collar workers in northern and central England were the main force behind the Brexit referendum and have always been distant from political leaders, forgotten by globalization, and marginalized by the so-called proxy — the EU.
The major cities in England — especially London — may have benefited greatly from globalization, but they have not received any benefits.
Due to a lack of confidence in Jeremy Corbyn, the leader of the Labour Party, many members of the blue-collar worker group ultimately became prey for the populist Brexit promises.
"We will reverse globalization," they said.
"We will drive out low-wage immigrants and redirect the hundreds of millions of pounds that were originally given to the EU to public services."
They promised that Brexit would bring back a safer and more prosperous past for the UK.
The Brexit supporters cannot truly fulfill these promises.
Globalization cannot be reversed, nor can the flow of immigrants from the EU be stopped.
Any such move would only destroy British businesses.
Even if the economic downturn leads to a decrease in immigration, the workers who voted for Brexit may still find low-paying jobs unappealing and face continued pressure on public services.
This is unlikely to lead to an increase in social cohesion.
The Brexit referendum has unleashed a difficult-to-control populist emotional storm.
Just like Donald Trump's inability to improve the situation of American working-class voters, Brexit will not bring benefits to those who chose it, no matter how things look.
Although it has many advantages, such a challenge May may still be unable to overcome.
